recordings.loc: Jacobson Park, Fayette County, Kentucky
Skidaway Island, Chatham County, GA USA
recordings.rmk:
I attached a recorder to the nest box and threaded the tiny microphone through the opening. The chicks are 1 day old at this point, and in full throat. The parent bird sings an entire phrase when entering the box, unlike a Carolina Wren I recorded last year, which used only a chip note to alert the nestlings. Even after the bird has flown, the nestlings continue to call feebly for a minute or so. I have shortened the file from its original 42 minutes, and also reduced the intervals between visits, which were unpredictable anyway. The intervals averaged approximately 3 minutes, 45 seconds, and varied between 2 minutes, 15 seconds, and 4 minutes, 30 seconds.

Recorder: Olympus LS-10
microphone: Senal CL-6

recordings.loc: New Jersey (near  West Cape May), Cape May County, New Jersey
recordings.rmk: This is a Carolina Chickadee with a vocal anomaly. The song and call patterns are normal, but the frequency is clearly off and may be a result of physical damage or developmental issue. The bird was singing from a reed bed (Phragmitis sp.) and some bare branches above the reed bed. I was without my binoculars and I did not physically see the bird, but I have no doubt of the ID.

recordings.loc: Oxford, Lafayette County, Mississippi
recordings.rmk:
Bird perched in a pussy willow as it approached a feeder next to which I was standing. The calls were directed at me, though I did not use playback or instigate the bird in any way other than by my presence. A second chickadee called from an adjacent oak tree approximately 5m away. The call increases in pitch after the bird retrieves a sunflower seed from the feeder (~1:14) and calls with the seed in its bill.

#Habitat#
Light urban lawn adjoining a forest fragment with some large mixed oak-hickory trees.

#Editing#
No edits.

#Equipment#
Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector.
